snippet.textDisplay: It's mostly for content or showing off .   They went too far on the scale and probably a single Noctua 15 fan blowing air would have had similar to the entire water cooler and probably hold around 40 degrees. TRX40 motherboard VRMs now come with built in 30mm fans and it's more than enough to bring down the temperature about 10 degrees.

snippet.textDisplay:
Lol I love all you guys talking about 4k, 6k and 8k.....the thing is though how many people are watching your stuff in anything but 720/1080P? I watched a video by a photographer named Tony Northrup and he's moving from 4K to high quality 1080P and Canon for video cause:
1) Despite being a high end camera reviewer and professional photographer nobody is really watching his videos in 4k.
2) People are commenting on how great his new 1080p video is looking.
3) He figured out his costs in workstations, camera gear and server space for all that 4k video and realized what a waste of money it was. Just in hardware alone. Then he figured out the time wasted making 4k vids and 1080p. After that all the 4k equipment is gone and we were none the wiser other than saying his vids looked better.😂
He figures nobody really watches high end HD because they don't have or can't afford the service needed and like a good mp3 versus a losssless format it's good enough for almost all people. Say what you will about new networking tech and fiber....how many people ACTUALLY have it or just watch your vids on their phones? Crap I have fiber wired to my building and I've been waiting 4 years for them to turn it on with no date in site. Even if they did all my monitors are either 1080p or 1440...I've no interest in upgrading.

snippet.textDisplay:
Out of curiosity, what made you choose that Sigma lens for your Reds? Did you ever compare it to something more expensive like some Zeiss glass for example? I have no clue when it comes to "digital cinema lenses", but it suprised me somewhat to stick a 4k lens to a 50k body. Since the lens is what dictates what the sensor can record it's usually the other way round when it comes to more down to earth sub 10k$ consumer to pro gear, put expensive glass onto a cheaper body to yield better results than the other way round. I realize there is much more stuff to consider here in terms of color rendition, bokeh and focussing, but i wonder how that Sigma 18-35 compares to some ten times more expensive Zeiss prime lens for example. Would have loved to see some technical review and concolusion with and without watercooling too, like imagequality wise, noise levels, image sharpness etc., go get some serious photo/video tech nerd and bench the shit out of your setup ;-)


Entertaining edit by the way, good job!
